<?xml version="1.0"?>
<html>
  <problem>
    <title> CheckPoint: Yo-Yo </title>

<p>A yo-yo has mass m and rotational inertia \(I\). A light thin string is wrapped around the central part of the yo-yo that has radius \(r\). The string is attached to the ceiling as shown. The yo-yo is released from rest and begins to descend as the string unwraps. The positive "y" direction is downward, as indicated by the arrow on the diagram.</p>
<br/>
<img src="/static/problems/MIT/rayyan/check_points/Pictures/BK89.PNG" alt="BK89"/>
<br/>

<p>Part 1. If the force of tension in the string is T, what is the correct expression that results from applying Newton's 2nd law on the motion of the center of mass of the yo-yo? Remember that downwards is treated as the positive direction in this problem.</p>

      <br/>
      <multiplechoiceresponse direction="vertical" randomize="no" type="MultipleChoice">
        <choicegroup type="MultipleChoice">
          <choice location="random" name="foil1" correct="true">
                  \( mg-T= ma  \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil2" correct="false">
                  \( T + mg = ma \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil3" correct="false">
                  Zero
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil4" correct="false">
                  \( mg - Tr = ma \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil5" correct="false">
                  \( mg + Tr = ma \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil6" correct="false">
                  \( Tr - mg = ma \)
          </choice>
        </choicegroup>
      </multiplechoiceresponse>

<br/>
<p>Part 2. With respect to the axis passing through the center of the yo-yo, what is the magnitude of the net torque acting on the yo-yo? Take clockwise rotation to be the positive direction.</p>

      <br/>
      <multiplechoiceresponse direction="vertical" randomize="no" type="MultipleChoice">
        <choicegroup type="MultipleChoice">
          <choice location="random" name="foil1" correct="false">
                  \( (mg - T)r \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil2" correct="false">
                  \( (mg + T)r \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil3" correct="false">
                  Zero
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil4" correct="true">
                  \( Tr     \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil5" correct="false">
                  \( mgr \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil6" correct="false">
                  \( 2Tr \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil7" correct="false">
                  \( 2mgr \)
          </choice>
        </choicegroup>
      </multiplechoiceresponse>

<br/>
<p>Part 3. What is the relationship between the translational acceleration of the yo-yo a and its angular acceleration \(\alpha\)?</p>

      <br/>
      <multiplechoiceresponse direction="vertical" randomize="no" type="MultipleChoice">
        <choicegroup type="MultipleChoice">
          <choice location="random" name="foil1" correct="true">
                  \( a= \alpha r \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil2" correct="false">
                  \( a= \alpha /r \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil4" correct="false">
                  \( a= 2\alpha r    \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil5" correct="false">
                  \( a= 2\alpha /r \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil6" correct="false">
                  \( a= \alpha r /2 \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil7" correct="false">
                  \( a= \alpha/(2r) \)
          </choice>
        </choicegroup>
      </multiplechoiceresponse>

<br/>
<p>Part 4. What is the downward acceleration of the yo-yo?</p>

      <br/>
      <multiplechoiceresponse direction="vertical" randomize="no" type="MultipleChoice">
        <choicegroup type="MultipleChoice">
          <choice location="random" name="foil1" correct="true">
                  \( a = g (mr^2)/(mr^2 + I) \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil2" correct="false">
                  \( a = g (mr^2 + I)/(mr^2)   \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil4" correct="false">
                  \( a = g (mr^2)/( I)   \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil5" correct="false">
                  \( a = g (I)/(mr^2) \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil6" correct="false">
                  \( a = g (I)/(mr^2 + I)    \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil7" correct="false">
                  \( a = g (mr^2 + I)/ I)        \)
          </choice>
        </choicegroup>
      </multiplechoiceresponse>

<br/>
<p>Part 5. What is the magnitude of the force of tension in the string?</p>

      <br/>
      <multiplechoiceresponse direction="vertical" randomize="no" type="MultipleChoice">
        <choicegroup type="MultipleChoice">
          <choice location="random" name="foil1" correct="false">
                  \( T = mg (mr^2)/(mr^2 + I) \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil2" correct="false">
                  \( T = mg (mr^2 + I)/(mr^2)   \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil4" correct="false">
                  \( T = mg (mr^2)/( I)   \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil5" correct="false">
                  \( T = mg (I)/(mr^2) \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil6" correct="true">
                  \( T = mg (I)/(mr^2 + I)    \)
          </choice>
          <choice location="random" name="foil7" correct="false">
                  \( T = mg (mr^2 + I)/ I)        \)
          </choice>
        </choicegroup>
      </multiplechoiceresponse>

</problem>
